## 4. Firebase Integration & Offline Sync

### Connection Architecture

Firebase Realtime Database is used for multi-device sync. It is entirely optional — if Firebase is unreachable, the app works offline using `localStorage` as the source of truth.

The Firebase connection state is monitored via `.info/connected` (not a fake check — this is the actual Firebase socket state) which drives the sync status dot visible in the header and drawer.

### Offline Queue

Every write that cannot reach Firebase (offline, or write fails) is saved to a persistent queue in `localStorage` under the key `afkSyncQueueV1`.

```javascript
function queuePending(action, collectionName, id, obj) {
  // Deduplicates by collection+id — a later write replaces an earlier one for the same record
  syncQueue = syncQueue.filter(q => !(q.collection===collectionName && q.id===id));
  syncQueue.push({ action, collection: collectionName, id, obj: obj||null, ts: Date.now() });
  saveSyncQueueToDisk();
}
```

When the device comes back online, `flushSyncQueue()` replays all queued operations. A `window.addEventListener('online', ...)` triggers this automatically.

### Firebase Real-Time Subscription

On connection, all 7 collections are subscribed with `.on('value', ...)`. Any change from another device appears immediately. On receiving new data:

1. The local `DB` array is replaced with the cloud version
2. `saveDB()` updates the localStorage cache
3. The active page is re-rendered live

### `undefined` Safety — The `sanitizeForFirebase()` Function

Firebase Realtime Database **silently fails** (or throws) when any nested property is JavaScript `undefined`. Older records may have fields that didn't exist at the time they were saved, leaving `undefined` when accessed. The app recursively replaces all `undefined` with `null` before any write:

```javascript
function sanitizeForFirebase(val) {
  if (val === undefined) return null;
  if (Array.isArray(val)) return val.map(sanitizeForFirebase);
  if (val && typeof val === 'object') {
    const out = {};
    Object.keys(val).forEach(k => { out[k] = sanitizeForFirebase(val[k]); });
    return out;
  }
  return val;
}
```

This makes writes forward-compatible — old records never break new fields.

