## 14. Feature: Notifications

### Notification Types

| Type | Trigger | Color |
|---|---|---|
| `overdue` | An invoice passes its credit due date | Red |
| `duplicate` | Two invoices for same customer on same day | Amber |
| `credit-limit` | Customer's outstanding exceeds their credit limit | Red |
| `wrong-password` | Incorrect PIN entered | Red |

### Overdue Notifications — Rate Limiting

Overdue checks run:
- 3 seconds after app start
- Every 15 minutes while the app is open

To prevent flooding, each invoice carries a `_overdueNotified` flag:
- Set to `true` when the notification is first created, persisted to Firebase
- The notification is not created again if `_overdueNotified === true`
- If the invoice is later paid (balance drops to zero), `_overdueNotified` is reset to `false` so a potential future relapse will notify again

### Notification Deduplication

The `addNotification()` function checks if a notification with the same `type + refId` already exists within the last 6 hours before creating a new one. This prevents duplicate alerts from repeated check runs.

### In-App Badge

The bell icon in the header shows a red badge with unread count. Navigating to the Notifications page marks all as read and clears the badge.

### Notification Routing

Tapping a notification opens the exact record it refers to:
- Overdue / Duplicate → `focusInvoice(id)` — clears all filters, finds the invoice in the list, scrolls to it, flashes it with a highlight animation
- Credit Limit → `focusCustomer(id)` — searches for the customer

### Startup Deduplication

`dedupeExistingNotifications()` runs once at startup to clean up any duplicate notifications that may have accumulated in Firebase before the deduplication logic was added.

### Device (Push) Notifications

If the user grants permission, the app sends operating-system-level notifications (like WhatsApp messages):

- Uses `Notification.requestPermission()` to ask for permission
- Sends via `ServiceWorkerRegistration.showNotification()` (preferred) or `new Notification()` fallback
- A daily "overdue summary" fires around 12pm noon (checked every 5 minutes)
- Periodic Background Sync registers `overdue-daily` with a 12-hour minimum interval, so the service worker can check even when the app is fully closed (supported in installed PWAs on Chrome/Samsung Internet)

